                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d430">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.0093/236: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-05-19T19:00:00+09:00"
                            >May 19, 1938—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 20—8 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>321. Peiping’s 305, May 18, 4 p.m., violation of the established rights of the
                    Legation quarter. We made today to the Foreign Office oral representations on
                    the basis of Peiping’s note to the Japanese Embassy, urging that the Japanese
                    military be directed to respect Legation quarter rights. According to the
                    Foreign Office, the visitors referred to are Prince Kanin the younger and Prince
                    Chichibu and they have already left Peiping. The Foreign Office stated that it
                        <pb facs="0332" n="328" xml:id="pg_328"/> would take up the matter at once
                    with the War Office with a view to appropriate instructions being sent to the
                    military authorities in Peiping.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping for Hankow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
